            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Electrical working, power and energy",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Dangers of electricity",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Safe use of electricity in the home",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Heating",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Heating",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "content" : [
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "Heating Effect of Electric Current: The heating effect of an electric current is the production of heat in a conductor when a current flows through it.",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "paragraph"
            }
          ],
          "name" : "Definition",
          "style" : "note",
          "type" : "aside"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "When a current flows through a conductor, the electrons collide with the atoms in the conductor. This causes the atoms to vibrate more, which is felt as heat.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Usually, heating elements are made of nichrome because it is highly resistant to heat and has a high melting point.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Electrical-Power-Consumption",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Electrical Power Consumption",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Electrical components have several ratings that are important to know when using them. These include:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Voltage rating, which is the voltage it is designed to operate at (it will usually start to fail above this rating)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Power rating, which is the power the component draws at its operational voltage",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "AC frequency, which is used by high-power components. You don’t need to calculate anything related to AC frequency.",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "For more on power, see ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "doc:\/\/Notes\/documentation\/Notes\/Current-of-Electricity#Power",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : ".",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "There are some other formulas which are of particular use when calculating power consumption:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\textrm{Voltage is the work done to move a unit charge from one point to another}",
            "V = W\/Q"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "where",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "V",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the voltage in volts (V)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "W",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the energy in joules (J)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "Q",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the charge in coulombs (C)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\textrm{Work done is the product of work done, current, and time}",
            "W = V \\times I \\times t"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "where",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "W",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the energy in joules (J)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "V",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the voltage in volts (V)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "I",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the current in amperes (A)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "t",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the time in seconds (s)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\textrm{The work done by the electric current is the electrical energy delivered}",
            "E = W"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "where",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "E",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the electrical energy in joules (J)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Calculating-Electrical-Cost",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Calculating Electrical Cost",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Each month, every household is billed for the amount of electrical energy they consume throughout the month",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "An electricity meter measures the amount of electrical energy consumed in kilowatt-hours (kWh)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "The cost of electricity is based on the energy unit of kilowatt-hours (kWh)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "1 \\textrm{ kWh} = 1000 \\textrm{ W} \\times 3600 \\textrm{ s} = 3.6 \\times 10^6 \\textrm{ J} = 3.6 \\textrm{ MJ}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "One kilowatt-hour is the energy consumed by a 1 kW appliance in one hour.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Electricity is sold at a rate, in dollars per kilowatt-hour ($\/kWh). Its usually equal to something between $0.12 and $0.25.",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "The cost of electricity can be calculated using the formula:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\textrm{Cost} = E \\times \\textrm{Cost per kWh}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Dangers-of-Electricity",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Dangers of Electricity",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Electricity can kill human beings (or really any living being) directly:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "The human body can withstand a current of about 50mA (current is the one that kills. Higher voltage just means more current.)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Large amount of current can cause burns or damage organs",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Electric current can cause involuntary muscle contractions. If this happens to the heart, it may cause it to stop.",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "It can also kill indirectly through fires.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "These hazards occur in three ways:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Damaged insulation",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Overloading of cables",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Damp conditions",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Damaged-Insulation",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Damaged Insulation",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Insulation is used to prevent electric current from flowing through the wrong path",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "If insulation is damaged (such as through fraying), the uninsulated wires may be exposed",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Current from the wires may flow through the wrong path, causing",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                },
                {
                  "items" : [
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "A short circuit, which can cause fires",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "Electric shock",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "unorderedList"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Overloading-of-Cables",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Overloading of Cables",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Cables have a maximum current they can carry",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "A large amount of current may pass through wires or plugs when too many components are connected together",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "This can cause the cables to overheat, which can cause fires",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Damp-Conditions",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Damp Conditions",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Impure or contaminated water is a good conductor of electricity",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "When water gets into electrical appliances, the water conducts electricity from the electrical element to the human body",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "This can cause electric shock",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Safe-Use-of-Electricity-in-the-Home",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Safe Use of Electricity in the Home",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "There are several ways to ensure that electricity is used safely in the home:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "header" : "row",
          "rows" : [
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Device",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Details",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "3-pin plug",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "fuse, earth wire, cable grip, double insulation",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Fuses in devices and 3-pin plugs",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "breaks the circuit when there is excessive current flowing in the device or 3-pin plugs",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Earthing of metal casings of devices",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "provides a very low resistance path for sudden surge of current (when casing becomes live)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Double insulation of devices",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "prevents casing from coming into contact with live wire in the event of electrical faults",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Placement of switch on live wire",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "always positioned at the live wire to cut off the appliance from high voltage mains effectively",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Circuit Breakers",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Mini-circuit breakers, Earth-leakage circuit breakers",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ],
            [
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Household main electrical wiring system",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ],
              [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "circuit breakers - breaks the circuit when there is excessive current flowing in circuit",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            ]
          ],
          "type" : "table"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "3-Pin-Plug",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "3 Pin Plug",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The 3-pin plug has three pins: live, neutral, and earth",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Live: Carries the current to the appliance",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Neutral: Completes the circuit",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Earth: Provides a path for the current to flow to the ground if the live wire comes into contact with the casing",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "It also includes a fuse, which breaks the circuit if the current is too high.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Fuses",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Fuses",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Fuses are used to break the circuit when there is excessive current flowing in the device or 3-pin plugs. They are made of a thin wire",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "that melts when the current is too high. This breaks the circuit and prevents the device from being damaged.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Fuses have a current rating. Generally, the current rating of the fuse should be slightly higher than the current that the device",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "draws. This is to prevent the fuse from breaking when the device is turned on, where it might draw slightly higher current than usual.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The fuse is connected to the LIVE wire, so that the current is cut off before it reaches the appliance. Same logic applies to switches.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Earthing-of-Metal-Casings-of-Devices",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Earthing of Metal Casings of Devices",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "When appliances have metal bodies, they are at risk of becoming live if the live wire comes into contact with the casing. This can",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "cause electric shock if someone touches the casing.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Earthing provides a very low resistance path for the sudden surge of current, which prevents the casing from becoming live. This is usually",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "achieved by an earth wire that is connected to the casing.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Circuit-Breakers",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Circuit Breakers",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "content" : [
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "Circuit Breaker: A device that automatically breaks the circuit when there is excessive current flowing in the circuit",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "paragraph"
            }
          ],
          "name" : "Definition",
          "style" : "note",
          "type" : "aside"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "There are two types of circuit breakers:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Earth Leakage Circuit Breakers (ELCB): Detects current leakage to the earth and breaks the circuit",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Miniature Circuit Breakers (MCB): Detects excessive current and breaks the circuit",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "columns" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "anchor" : "Miniature-Circuit-Breakers",
                  "level" : 4,
                  "text" : "Miniature Circuit Breakers",
                  "type" : "heading"
                },
                {
                  "items" : [
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "Prevents excessive current flow through a circuit by breaking or tripping it.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "Usually, it is set at 10 A, 15 A or 20 A.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "When the MCB trips, it means that there is an overloading of devices.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "It is recommended that some devices are switched off before turning the MCB back on again.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "unorderedList"
                }
              ],
              "size" : 1
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "anchor" : "Earth-Leakage-Circuit-Breakers",
                  "level" : 4,
                  "text" : "Earth Leakage Circuit Breakers",
                  "type" : "heading"
                },
                {
                  "items" : [
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "It monitors the current leakage (difference in current between the live and the neutral wire).",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        },
                        {
                          "items" : [
                            {
                              "content" : [
                                {
                                  "inlineContent" : [
                                    {
                                      "text" : "In normal operation, the current in the live and neutral wire should be the same. A disparity implies that some current is leaking to the earth.",
                                      "type" : "text"
                                    }
                                  ],
                                  "type" : "paragraph"
                                }
                              ]
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "unorderedList"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "When this difference in current is greater than 30 mA, the circuit breaker is tripped.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "When the ELCB trips, it means that there is a leakage of current through a faulty device.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "content" : [
                        {
                          "inlineContent" : [
                            {
                              "text" : "Identify the faulty device and get it repaired or stop using it.",
                              "type" : "text"
                            }
                          ],
                          "type" : "paragraph"
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "unorderedList"
                }
              ],
              "size" : 1
            }
          ],
          "numberOfColumns" : 2,
          "type" : "row"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
